[00:00] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'Hello everyone. I\'m Milo. I\'m one of the co-founders and developers of Panggalin. In about two or three minutes, I\'m going to show you how quick and easy it is to connect any network to Panggalin and then securely and privately access any application, service or infrastructure running behind a firewall. Penglin is'

[00:13] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'unique in that it provides direct VPN like access to resources and it also provides web-based public ingress to resources like a Cloudflare tunnel or Enrock. I already have an account created at app.penglin.net net and I\'m'

[00:25] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'logged in with my organization\'s identity provider. So the next step is to create a site and a site is an entry point into any network. So in this example, I\'m going to use an EC2 hosted on AWS in a VPC and this is going to be'

[00:37] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'natted behind a firewall. Scrolling down, I\'m given credentials and easy commands to run the connector on any platform, whether that\'s Unix, Windows, or even Docker. I\'m going to choose the Docker run command because that\'s the'

[00:49] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'simplest and easiest way for me to run that on my EC2. Then I\'m going to copy the command and then just go ahead and create the site. Now going over to my EC2, I can simply run this command and it\'ll go ahead and start up that connector. Back in the dashboard, I can now go to my sites and I\'ll see my sites'

[01:01] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'online, which is great. And then I can create a private resource. So a private resource is how you grant access to specific applications, services or infrastructure. So in this case, I\'m just going to create an SSH resource that gives me SSH access uh to that EC2.'

[01:14] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'I\'m going to uh put in the destination as a local host because it\'s the same host running the connector. and then give it a nice friendly alias like EC2.in internal. The next step is to grant access policies. So I can give'

[01:27] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'specific users and specific roles access to this resource. So maybe I want my members to all be able to SSH in. And then under network settings, I can also restrict the firewall settings of the specific resource. So I can shape that'

[01:40] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'resource more specifically. Uh for SSH, all I need is port 22 on TCP. I can block all UDP traffic and I also don\'t need ICMP enabled. Now I can actually connect. I already have my Penglin'

[01:52] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'client launched and we support clients on all the major platforms from Mac OS to iOS to Android. The Mac OS app just lives in the top menu bar here and a nice icon. You authenticate with your Penglin account. Then you can connect.'

[02:04] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'But first, I\'m going to go back to my terminal and then demonstrate that I can\'t SSH into my EC2. It\'ll actually just fail here because I\'m not connected. But then once I go ahead and connect, then I should be able to uh SSH into that machine. You\'ll notice that'

[02:17] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'I\'m using a friendly alias name that I set earlier. Let\'s go ahead and try now. There we go. I\'m connected in the Penguin client. If I check the settings, I can actually see under the status page that I\'m connected to that EC2. And this'

[02:30] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'is a direct connection. So, it\'s peer-to-peer punches through the NAT. Uh, and if it can\'t punch, then it will relay through a Penguin server. Penguin also supports public resource exposure through that same connector we'

[02:42] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'installed. So, for example, I already have Graphfana running on this system. This is very useful to expose dashboards like Graphfana because they\'re web- based and can be accessed anywhere from any web browser without a client connected. I have Graphana running on'

[02:55] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'port 3000 internally on this EC2. So I can go ahead and create a quick resource in Penglin called Graphana and then give it a custom domain name. If you use Penglin Cloud, we provide a handful of free domain ending names. So I\'m just'

[03:09] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'going to call this Graphfana test. Select one of the free domain names and then select a target. So this is similar to the destination of the private resource, but this has to point to Graphfana running on port 3000 on that'

[03:21] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'EC2 instance. I\'ll go ahead and create it. And actually, by default, authentication is enabled. So users will have to first log in with their Penguin account before they can get browserbased access. And just to demonstrate that this works when not connected with a'

[03:34] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'Penguin client, I\'ll go ahead and disconnect. And now I can still access my Graphana dashboard from wherever. Penglin is a powerful remote access platform for giving specific users access to specific resources on private networks. It\'s open source and it\'s'

[03:47] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'based on WireGuard.'
